{"cursor":"21059","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nA 'negotiable instrument' is a document guaranteeing the payment of a specific\namount of money, either on demand, or at a set time, without conditions in\naddition to payment imposed on the payer. Cheques or promissory notes are common\nexamples. Negotiable instruments are often defined in legislation. For\nexample, according to the Section 13 of the Negotiable Instruments Act, 1881 in\nIndia, a negotiable instrument is a promissory note, bill of exchange or cheque\npayable either to order or to bearer. Cheque also includes [[demand draft]]\n[Section 85A]. Although often discussed as foundational in commercial law,\ntheir modern relevance is sometimes questioned.\n\nMore precisely, it is a document contemplated by a contract, which (1) warrants\nthe payment of money, the promise of or order for conveyance of which is\nunconditional; (2) specifies or describes the payee, who is designated on and\nmemorialized by the instrument; and (3) is capable of change through transfer by\nvalid negotiation (sale) of the instrument. When the instrument is transferred\nin accordance with certain conditions, the holder may become a holder in due\ncourse and be free from defenses which would apply to the original payee, such\nas defective goods or fraud.\n\nInstruments can be transferred for amounts in contractual exchange that are less\nthan the instrumentâs face value (known as âdiscountingâ), particularly if there\nis doubt as to the payer's ability to pay. Under United States law, Article 3 of\nthe Uniform Commercial Code as enacted in applicable state law governs the use\nof negotiable instruments, except banknotes (âFederal Reserve Notesâ, a.k.a.\n\"paper dollars\")..\n","linknr":248,"url":"Negotiable_instrument","recorded":1374785754,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Negotiable_instrument&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Negotiable_instrument&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico",